a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes n k :: nat
assumes h0 : "n = 10"
and h1 : "k = 5"
shows  "binomial n k = 252"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 Compute $\dbinom{10}{5}$. The final Answer is 252
 ### Proof
 \begin{align} \dbinom{10}{5} &= \dfrac{10!}{5!5!} \\ &= \dfrac{10\times9\times 8\times 7\times 6}{5\times 4\times 3\times 2\times 1} \\ &= \dfrac{10}{5}\times \dfrac{9}{3} \times \dfrac{8}{4} \times \dfrac{7}{1} \times \dfrac{6}{2} \\
 &= 2\times 3\times 2\times 7\times 3 \\ &= \boxed{252}. \end{align}
 *)

theorem
fixes n k :: nat
assumes h0 : "n = 10"
and h1 : "k = 5"
shows  "binomial n k = 252"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer
a_0.informal problem: Calculate the binomial coefficient for $n=10$ and $k=5$. The final answer is 252.
